-- CHRONOLOGY: China's measures to cool its economy
-- 
-- Fri Jul 20, 2007 6:55am EDT
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/07/20/us-china-economy-rates-idUSPEK36087320070720

 

 BEIJING  (Reuters) - China's central bank raised interest rates on Friday in the latest in a series of tightening steps to prevent the world's fourth-biggest economy from overheating. 

     Following are some of the steps taken since mid-2003 JULY 20, 2007 - Central bank raises one-year deposit rate 0.27 percentage point to 3.33 percent and the one-year lending rate by 0.27 percentage point to 6.84 percent, effective July 21. Sight deposit rate also raised to 0.81 percent from 0.72 percent. JULY 1, 2007 - China reduces or abolishes value-added tax rebates on 37 percent of its export categories to deter exports of energy-intensive products. MAY 21, 2007 -- China imposes a 5-10 percent export tax on more than 80 types of steel products, effective June 1. MAY 18, 2007 -- The central bank raises the one-year lending rate by 0.18 percentage point and the one-year deposit rate by 0.27 percentage point, effective May 19, bringing them to 6.57 percent and 3.06 percent, respectively. At the same time, it raises banks' reserve requirement by 0.5 percentage point, effective June 5. It also widens the yuan's daily trading band against the dollar to 0.5 percent from 0.3 percent. APRIL 29, 2007 -- The central bank raises banks' reserve requirement by 0.5 percentage point, effective May 15. APRIL 10, 2007 -- China removes export rebates on most types of steel products and reduces the rebate on more value-added products to 5 percent, effective Apr. 15. APRIL 5, 2007 -- The central bank raises banks' reserve requirement by 0.5 percentage point, effective Apr. 16. MARCH 30, 2007 -- Eight Chinese ministries say they will launch year-long checks into property market irregularities. MARCH 17, 2007 -- China raises the one-year benchmark yuan deposit rate by 0.27 percentage points to 2.79 percent and the one-year benchmark lending rate by the same amount to 6.39 percent, effective March 18. FEBRUARY 16, 2007 -- The central bank raises banks' reserve requirement by 0.5 percentage point to 10 percent for big banks and 10.5 percent for smaller ones, effective February 25. JANUARY 17, 2007 -- China's tax bureau says it will start levying a long-awaited land appreciation tax, from February 1. JANUARY 5, 2007 -- The central bank raises banks' reserve requirement by 0.5 percentage point, effective January 15. NOVEMBER 3, 2006 -- The central bank raises commercial banks' reserve requirements by 0.5 percentage point, effective November 15. OCTOBER 18, 2006 -- Premier Wen Jiabao says in a published speech to the cabinet that Beijing would keep a tight grip on bank lending and land supply. SEPTEMBER 14, 2006 -- China's Ministry of Finance says it would cut tax or scrap tax rebates for steel, non-ferrous, coal, natural gas and others, while increase those for high-tech and heavy machinery equipment products, effective on September 15, to trim its trade surplus. SEPTEMBER 5, 2006 -- Xinhua cites a cabinet notice as saying that China had issued new rules on land use, laying out punishments for local leaders who fail to investigate or halt illegal sales. AUGUST 18, 2006 -- The central bank raises commercial banks' one-year deposit and lending rates by 0.27 percentage point, to 2.52 percent and 6.12 percent respectively, effective August 19. AUGUST 16, 2006 -- In the first such action against provincial leaders, the State Council punishes three senior Inner Mongolia officials for building a power station without Beijing's approval. AUGUST 2, 2006 -- The top planning agency orders an urgent audit of all investment projects begun this year costing more than 100 million yuan ($13.22 million) to ensure they meet central-government land use, credit and other policy guidelines. JULY 21, 2006 -- The central bank raises reserve requirements for big state banks and joint-stock banks by half a percentage point to 8.5 percent and raises the reserve ratio to 9.0 percent for smaller banks, effective August 15. JUNE 16, 2006 -- The central bank raises reserve requirements for big state banks by half a percentage point to 8.0 percent and for smaller banks to 8.5 percent. The rise, effective July 5, will drain 150 billion yuan from the banking system. MAY 29, 2006 -- As part of a package of measures to deter property speculation, China's cabinet raises the downpayment requirement for those seeking mortgages to 30 percent from 20 percent. Houses smaller than 90 sq m and owner-occupiers are exempt. APRIL 27, 2006 -- The central bank raises bank lending rates for the first time in 18 months. The one-year bank lending rate rises to 5.85 percent from 5.58 percent, but deposit rates stay unchanged. JULY 21, 2005 -- China revalues the yuan by 2.1 percent to 8.11 per dollar and scraps a decade-long peg to the dollar, setting the yuan free to float within managed bands against a basket of currencies. OCTOBER 28, 2004 -- The central bank raises interest rates for the first time in nine years. The benchmark one-year yuan lending rate rises to 5.58 percent from 5.31 percent, and the rate on one-year deposits goes up to 2.25 percent from 1.98 percent. At the same time, it scraps the upper ceiling on bank lending rates. MAY 12, 2004 -- China's central bank expands open-market operations to twice a week from once weekly to better control money supply. APRIL 29-30, 2004 -- The government punishes party and bank officials for letting an iron-and-steel firm illegally obtain land and bank loans. It orders checks into most fixed-asset investment projects, warning many may be cancelled if found to be improper. APRIL 29, 2004 -- China orders some smaller banks to halt lending for several days to clamp down on easy credit. APRIL 11, 2004 -- Central bank raises bank reserve requirements for all banks by half a percentage point to 7.5 percent and raises reserve ratio to eight percent for smaller lenders. MARCH 25, 2004 -- The central bank raises reserve requirements for banks with lower capital adequacy by half a percentage point to 7.5 percent, targeting smaller local lenders. JANUARY 1, 2004 -- The Ministry of Commerce trims export tax rebates to slow export growth, which is putting upward pressure on the yuan.